From: Chris Wetzel <chris@cwetzel.com>
Subject: [PATCH] intel_idle: add Tiger Lake CPU idle state support

Tiger Lake (model 0x8D) and Tiger Lake-L (model 0x8C) are missing from
the intel_idle CPU ID table, causing the driver to fall back to
ACPI-enumerated C-states. On Dell XPS 9510 (i7-11800H), the BIOS only
exposes 3 ACPI C-states (C1, ~C7, C10) instead of the 8 native states
available in the Skylake-family table (C1, C1E, C3, C6, C7s, C8, C9,
C10). This results in suboptimal power/latency tradeoffs for short and
medium idle periods.

Tiger Lake uses Willow Cove cores with the same MWAIT C-state hints as
Skylake/Kaby Lake, so map both variants to idle_cpu_skl (skl_cstates).
The driver validates each MWAIT substate at boot and skips any the
hardware doesn't support, so this mapping is safe even if future
firmware changes the available substates.

Signed-off-by: Chris Wetzel <chris@cwetzel.com>
---
 drivers/idle/intel_idle.c | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)

--- a/drivers/idle/intel_idle.c
+++ b/drivers/idle/intel_idle.c
@@ -1586,6 +1586,8 @@ static const struct x86_cpu_id intel_idle_ids[] __initconst = {
 	X86_MATCH_VFM(INTEL_KABYLAKE,		&idle_cpu_skl),
 	X86_MATCH_VFM(INTEL_SKYLAKE_X,		&idle_cpu_skx),
 	X86_MATCH_VFM(INTEL_ICELAKE_X,		&idle_cpu_icx),
+	X86_MATCH_VFM(INTEL_TIGERLAKE_L,	&idle_cpu_skl),
+	X86_MATCH_VFM(INTEL_TIGERLAKE,		&idle_cpu_skl),
 	X86_MATCH_VFM(INTEL_ICELAKE_D,		&idle_cpu_icx),
 	X86_MATCH_VFM(INTEL_ALDERLAKE,		&idle_cpu_adl),
 	X86_MATCH_VFM(INTEL_ALDERLAKE_L,	&idle_cpu_adl_l),
